accesses.location: CITY PARK AND HWY RIGHT-OF-WAY SURROUND ALL BUT SE CORNER OF THE EASTERN BASIN.

surveys.narrative: BLB AND NOP DOMINATE THE CURRENT FISH POPULATION. BLB WERE CAPTURED AT 15 TIMES THE LOCAL MEDIAN FOR GILL NETS AND 3.5 TIMES THE LOCAL MEDIAN FOR TRAP NETS. SIZE OF THE FISH WAS SMALL, WITH A MEDIAN RANGE OF 6.5-6.9 INCHES TOTAL LENGTH AND AN OVERALL RANGE OF 4.5-8.9 INCHES. BLB AVERAGE RATE WAS 5.0 FISH PER POUND. NOP WERE SAMPLED AT DOUBLE THE LOCAL MEDIAN FOR GILL NETS AND FOUR TIMES THE LOCAL MEDIANS FOR TRAP NETS. THE RSD= 8.3% FOR SAMPLED NOP. GROWTH OF NOP IS AVERAGE FOR ALL AGES. THREE CAP, TWO WTS, THREE BLG, AND SIX BLC WERE ALSO SAMPLED DURING THIS POPULATION ASSESSMENT.

WHITE SUCKER, BLACK BULLHEAD, YELLOW BULLHEAD, NORTHERN PIKE, AND PUMPKINSEED WERE FOUND AT OR ABOVE LOCAL MEDIAN NUMBERS. CARP, BLUEGILL, AND BLACK CRAPPIE WERE SAMPLED AT BELOW LOCAL MEDIAN LEVELS. SUCKERS AND CARP ARE LARGE INDIVIDUALS, AND NUMBERS OF CARP ARE SIGNIFICANTLY LOWER THAN IN 1978. REPRODUCTION OF NORTHERN PIKE IS GOOD, WHILE REPRODUCTION AND SURVIVAL OF PANFISH IS POOR AND AFFECTED BY WATER LEVEL FLUCTUATIONS.

NORTHERN PIKE CAPTURED AT AVERAGE NUMBERS AND SIZE THEY WERE FOUND TO BE III, IV, AND V YEARS OLD AND EXHIBITED AVERAGE GROWTH. BLACK CRAPPIES AND BLUEGILLS ARE SMALL. HIGH CATCH RATE ON CRAPPIES AND LOW CATCH RATE ON BLUEGILLS - ONE THIRD THE LOCAL MEDIAN. NUMBERS OF BLUEGILLS AND CRAPPIE ARE EFFECTED BY ANNUAL STOCKING OF CATCHABLE SIZE FISH. PUMPKINSEEDS AND YELLOW PERCH WERE PRESENT IN SMALL NUMBERS. YELLOW BULLHEADS WERE SAMPLED AT AVERAGE; ABUNDANCE. CARP, GOLDEN SHINER AND WHITE SUCKER WERE SAMPLED AT LEVELS ABOVE THE MEDIAN CATCH RATES. BLACK BULLHEADS WERE VERY ABUNDANT AND ARE THOUGHT TO CONTRIBUTE SIGNIFI- CANTLY TO THE POOR WATER CLARITY OF THIS LAKE. TWO SILVER REDHORSE AND SEVEN GOLDEN REDHORSE WERE ALSO SAMPLED.

Due to other operations the nets set in Champlin Mill Pond had to remain for two days rather than one. Carp, Blk Bullhead, Yel Bullhead and N Pike all appear to be present in numbers greater than the average. Wht Sucker, Pumpkinseed, Bluegill, Wht Crappie and Blk Crappie all appear to be less abundant than the average.

Champlin Mill Pond is 34-acre impoundment of Elm Creek that sits adjacent to and flows into the Mississippi River. The pond is on the site of a historic mill and the old dam was replaced in 2016. Lower Champlin Mill Pond near the dam was dewatered and dredged to increase the maximum depth to 15 feet in the fall of 2017.

Champlin Mill Pond is reported as an important recreational fishing location to the surrounding community. A standard lake survey was conducted in June of 2017.
Eleven Northern Pike were sampled in gillnets, an abundance well-above the average for similar lakes. Northern Pike in Champlin Mill Pond were small, averaging 1.6 pounds, a value below average in similar lakes. The average length was 18.9 inches and Northern Pike ranged from 16.0 inches to 22.3 inches in the lake.

Bluegill abundance and size in were below average compared to similar lakes. Bluegill measured 4.8 inches on average and ranged from 2.9-8.3 inches. Some natural reproduction may be occurring in the lake as suggested by fish aged 1 and 2 years that were sampled. Champlin Mill Pond was most recently stocked with Bluegill (150 fish) in spring 2014.

Champlin Mill Pond is managed as a children's fishing pond and is stocked annually in the spring with adult bluegills and black crappies. The black crappie population is average for this type of a lake. The fish sampled had an average length of 7.2 inches and an average weight of 0.2 pounds. Only three bluegills were sampled during the survey. They had an average length of 6.2 inches. Black bullheads and white suckers were both very abundant. The white sucker population is considered above average for this lake. The Black bullheads were the most abundant fish sampled in the nets, but are still considered average when compared to similar lakes.Northern pike numbers were the highest since 1984. The average size of northern pike had a length of 21.7 inches and had an average weight of 2.5 pounds.Yellow perch, yellow bullheads, white crappies, and hybrid sunfish were all sampled in low abundance. This is the first survey since 1989 that yellow perch and yellow bullheads were sampled, and the first time overall that white crappies and hybrid sunfish were sampled.Bowfin, pumpkinseed sunfish, and carp were all sampled in average numbers for this type of lake.
